---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Telehealth Platform for GP Practice — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a Brisbane GP practice build a Medicare-compliant telehealth platform serving regional Queensland patients 200km+ away — reaching 300+ teleconsults per week within three months of launch.',
  industry: 'Healthcare',
  tags: ['React', 'WebRTC', 'Medicare Integration', 'eRx Prescriptions', 'AWS'],
  title: 'Telehealth Platform for GP Practice',
  summary: 'A four-doctor GP practice in suburban Brisbane was turning away patients who couldn\'t make it in — some living more than 200 kilometres away. We built a Medicare-compliant telehealth platform with integrated digital prescriptions that went from zero to 300+ consultations per week in three months.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Doctor on a video consultation screen with a split view showing the consultation notes panel and prescription issuance workflow on the right',

  clientOverview: 'A four-doctor general practice in suburban Brisbane, operating for nine years with a patient base that had expanded well beyond its immediate catchment area — partly through word of mouth, partly through bulk billing, and partly because two of the GPs had developed specialisations in chronic disease management that drew patients from across regional Queensland. The practice had a waiting list for new patients and was frequently fielding requests from existing patients who had since moved to regional areas but did not want to change doctors.',
  clientSize: '4 GPs, 3 practice nurses, 2 admin staff',
  clientLocation: 'Brisbane, QLD',

  pullQuote: 'We\'d been telling patients in Toowoomba and Gympie to find a local GP for years because we couldn\'t see them. Now we can, properly and compliantly. The prescription piece especially — that was the thing that made it real.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Senior GP & Practice Principal',
  pullQuoteRole: 'Brisbane GP Practice',

  challenge: [
    'The situation before the project started was one the practice\'s principal GP found genuinely uncomfortable. Patients who had been with the practice for years, managing complex chronic conditions, were having to find new GPs when they moved away — not because the doctors wanted them to, but because there was no compliant, workable way to continue seeing them remotely. The occasional Zoom call had been tried informally during the pandemic, but it wasn\'t appropriate for ongoing care: no documentation, no prescription pathway, no proper billing.',
    'Medicare\'s telehealth bulk billing rules are specific and not trivial to implement correctly. A telehealth consultation that doesn\'t meet the documentation requirements — including the requirement that an ongoing patient relationship exists, the consultation type is appropriate for video delivery, and the clinical notes meet the same standard as an in-person visit — can result in a rejected or clawed-back claim. The practice had seen this happen to colleagues who\'d implemented telehealth hastily during the pandemic, and they were not willing to take shortcuts.',
    'The existing video tools the practice had briefly experimented with — Zoom, FaceTime, and one consumer telehealth app — all had the same problem: they sat completely outside the practice\'s clinical workflow. Doctors were conducting video calls and then manually writing everything up in their desktop clinical software afterwards, doubling the documentation effort. There was no way to issue a prescription during or immediately after the call without the patient physically receiving a paper document or the doctor calling a pharmacy directly.',
    'The prescription problem was the one the GPs felt most acutely. Australia\'s digital prescription system (eRx and the Electronic Prescribing regulations) had matured enough by the time we began this project that digital-only prescriptions were fully legal and supported by most major pharmacy dispensing systems. But implementing it required correct integration with the eRx token system, proper prescriber authentication, and making sure the workflow felt natural enough that GPs under time pressure would actually use it rather than defaulting to paper.',
    'Beyond clinical compliance, there was the matter of patient access. Regional Queensland patients dealing with chronic conditions — Type 2 diabetes, hypertension, chronic respiratory illness — needed reliable, high-quality video. A solution that degraded in poor connectivity areas was not good enough. The GPs were explicit about this: if the platform wasn\'t reliable enough for patients in areas with limited NBN access, it wasn\'t useful for the core use case.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The practice found us through a referral from a medical software consultant they\'d used for other projects. We were brought in specifically because of our previous work on healthcare systems and our familiarity with Medicare\'s billing API and the Australian Digital Health Agency\'s technical ecosystem. The principal GP had done enough research to know that WebRTC video could be implemented through several providers, but that the Medicare and eRx integration pieces were where projects like this tended to fail — either technically or through non-compliance.',
    'We had one introductory meeting where we walked through the Medicare telehealth billing rules in detail and described specifically how we\'d approached claim submission on a previous project. That meeting set the tone for the whole engagement. The GPs were medically trained and technically literate. They didn\'t want high-level reassurances — they wanted to understand the implementation. We were comfortable going deep on the technical and regulatory detail, and that built trust quickly.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'We started by mapping the full clinical consultation workflow in detail — not the technology workflow, but the clinical one. What does a GP do in the five minutes before a consultation, during it, and after it? What clinical information do they need visible during a video call that they have on their desk in an in-person consultation? What is the minimum viable documentation for a bulk-billed telehealth claim? We answered these questions in collaboration with the GPs before making any technical decisions.',
    'The Medicare telehealth billing rules formed the backbone of the system design. Every claim pathway we built was traced directly to the relevant Medicare Benefits Schedule item numbers and the associated documentation requirements. We brought in a medical billing consultant for a half-day review of our proposed claim submission approach before we wrote the code. This cost us a few thousand dollars in consulting fees and saved what could have been a significantly more expensive compliance problem later.',
    'For the video layer, we evaluated three options: building on Twilio Video (WebRTC), Daily.co, and a smaller Australian provider. We chose Twilio Video for its proven reliability, adaptive bitrate handling (critical for regional patients with variable connectivity), and the fact that it gave us the most control over the session lifecycle — we needed to be able to tie call start and end times directly to the clinical record and billing claim. The trade-off was slightly more implementation complexity than a higher-abstraction provider would have involved.',
    'The eRx integration was prototyped early and tested against the eRx sandbox environment for several weeks before we committed to the production integration approach. The token generation and prescription transmission flow is technically reliable, but it required careful handling of prescriber authentication — GPs authenticate with their prescriber number, and the system had to handle cases where a GP was prescribing on behalf of the practice versus as an individual, which affects how the token is generated.',
    'We built the DVA (Department of Veterans\' Affairs) claim pathway alongside the Medicare pathway from the start, rather than as an afterthought. A meaningful proportion of the practice\'s regional patients were DVA card holders, and the GPs had flagged this early. DVA telehealth billing has slightly different eligibility criteria than Medicare; building both pathways concurrently let us share most of the infrastructure while handling the differences correctly.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The platform is a React web application that GPs access from their usual workstation. The patient-facing side is also web-based — no app download required, which was an important usability decision for older and less tech-comfortable patients. Patients receive an SMS link before their appointment; clicking it opens their browser, grants camera and microphone access, and places them in a waiting room. The GP sees a notification that the patient is ready and joins the call with one click.',
    'During the consultation, the GP has a split-screen view: the video call on one side, and a structured consultation notes form on the other. The notes form prompts for the information required for a compliant telehealth Medicare claim — clinical indication, consultation type, whether ongoing patient relationship criteria are met — and surfaces any warnings if the GP tries to submit without completing required fields. This was a deliberate design choice: the compliance requirements are embedded in the workflow rather than existing as a separate checklist.',
    'Prescriptions are issued directly from the consultation interface. The GP selects a medication, enters the dose and repeats, and the prescription is transmitted to the eRx system, generating a token that can be sent to the patient by SMS. The patient takes the SMS to any participating pharmacy. The entire flow — from "this patient needs metformin" to "the patient has a valid prescription token on their phone" — takes under 90 seconds. Before the project, the equivalent process for a remote patient involved a fax to their local pharmacy and a phone call to confirm receipt.',
    'Billing is handled automatically after each consultation. Once the GP marks a consultation as complete and confirms the billing item, the system submits a bulk billing assignment form electronically and queues the Medicare claim. Rejected claims are surfaced in a daily exceptions report rather than being lost. The practice manager can see the status of every claim in real time, which was not previously possible.',
    'We also built a simple patient-facing scheduling component — patients can request telehealth appointments through the practice\'s website rather than having to call. This was a late-addition to scope, requested by the practice manager after she saw how many of the initial telehealth bookings were coming from patients who had called the practice specifically to ask for video appointments. It added about three weeks to the project but meaningfully changed the patient experience.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'We ran a four-week pilot with two of the four GPs before rolling out to the full practice. The pilot GPs were the two who were most enthusiastic about the project — choosing the most resistant doctors for a pilot is rarely productive. Feedback from the pilot was focused on the consultation notes form: the GPs wanted to be able to dictate notes rather than type them during a video call. We integrated browser-based speech-to-text as a result, which added a week to the timeline but was widely adopted once available.',
    'Patient onboarding for the regional cohort required more support than we\'d anticipated. Some patients had never done a video call of any kind; a few were using older devices or browsers that had compatibility issues with the WebRTC implementation. We worked with the practice to create a simple pre-consultation test page that patients could use to confirm their camera and microphone were working before their appointment time. This reduced the rate of failed connection attempts in the first minute of consultations from about 18% in the first week to under 4% by the fourth week.',
    'The DVA billing pathway needed additional testing after we discovered that DVA\'s online claiming system had a different response structure from its documented API specification in one edge case involving co-payment exemptions. We found this during load testing rather than in production, but it underscored why we\'d built extensive logging into the claims pipeline from the start. The issue was resolved in collaboration with DVA\'s provider helpdesk, and the fix was straightforward once we\'d identified the discrepancy.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'Building the compliance requirements into the consultation workflow — rather than as a separate compliance checklist — was the single best design decision we made. In earlier prototypes, we\'d had the compliance prompts as a separate step after the consultation ended. GPs consistently ignored them when they were running behind. Embedding them in the notes form itself, with soft warnings during and a blocking requirement on submission, achieved close to 100% compliance documentation without creating a significant workflow burden.',
    'The speech-to-text addition taught us something about scoping healthcare software projects. GPs are high-context, high-pressure users. Features that feel like "nice to have" from a product perspective can actually be critical to adoption when the alternative is adding cognitive load to someone who is simultaneously managing a clinical conversation. We\'ve since made "what happens to this user when they\'re under time pressure" a standard question in our healthcare requirements process.',
    'We had planned to offer a native mobile app for the patient side in a future phase, but the data from the first six months suggested it was not necessary: 91% of patient sessions were completed on either a smartphone browser or a desktop browser, and the satisfaction scores were high. The web-based approach also meant that patients on unusual or older devices — a genuine concern for elderly regional patients — were far less likely to hit compatibility issues than they would have been with a native app requiring a minimum OS version.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Six months after launch, the practice requested a patient-held chronic disease management module — a secure patient portal where patients managing conditions like diabetes or hypertension could log readings (blood glucose, blood pressure) between consultations, and GPs could review trends before telehealth appointments. This became its own project and significantly changed what the GPs were able to do in a 10-minute follow-up call: rather than asking "how have your numbers been this week?" they could arrive at the call already knowing.',
    'There is active discussion about expanding to two additional GP practices in the same network, which would mean multi-practice support in the admin layer and shared patient records where consent has been given. This is a meaningful architectural change that we\'ve already begun scoping.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'Three months after launch, the practice was handling over 300 telehealth consultations per week — a volume that had grown organically as word spread among the existing patient base. The bulk billing claim error rate has remained below 1.2%, which is better than the industry benchmark for telehealth billing. Practice revenue increased 31% in the first year, driven by the new telehealth volume and the reduction in wasted appointment slots from patients who couldn\'t attend in person.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '300+', label: 'Teleconsults per week', context: 'Reached within 3 months of launch, grown from zero' },
    { value: '94km', label: 'Average patient distance', context: 'Average distance of telehealth patients from practice' },
    { value: '<1.2%', label: 'Bulk billing claim error rate', context: 'Compared to ~8% industry average for new telehealth implementations' },
    { value: '+31%', label: 'Increase in practice revenue', context: 'First full year after telehealth launch vs prior year' },
    { value: 'Same day', label: 'Prescription fulfillment', context: 'Digital eRx tokens issued during consultation; previously 2 days via fax' },
    { value: '4.7/5', label: 'Patient satisfaction score', context: 'Average rating from post-consultation patient survey, first 6 months' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Responsive consultation interface with complex split-panel layout and real-time state' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'Backend API server; well-suited to the WebSocket connections needed for session management' },
    { name: 'Twilio Video (WebRTC)', reason: 'Adaptive bitrate, reliable regional performance, fine-grained session lifecycle control' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Consultation records, patient data, billing claims — all relationally structured' },
    { name: 'AWS (Sydney region)', reason: 'Healthcare data sovereignty requirements; all patient data stays in Australia' },
    { name: 'Medicare/DVA Integration', reason: 'Direct electronic bulk billing claim submission via approved claim channel' },
    { name: 'eRx Electronic Prescribing', reason: 'Digital prescription token generation and transmission; integrated with national eRx platform' },
    { name: 'Twilio SMS', reason: 'Patient appointment links, prescription token delivery, consultation reminders' },
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: 'Patient Management & Appointment System',
      href: '/case-studies/patient-management-appointment-system',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A Melbourne multi-specialist clinic replaced paper appointment books, fax referrals and disconnected billing with a fully integrated digital practice management platform.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Prescription Tracker & Medication Reminder App',
      href: '/case-studies/prescription-tracker-medication-app',
      industry: 'Healthcare',
      summary: 'A Perth compounding pharmacy built a patient-facing mobile app with medication reminders and dispensing software integration that improved adherence rates by 44%.',
    },
    {
      title: 'Customer Service AI Chatbot',
      href: '/case-studies/customer-service-ai-chatbot',
      industry: 'AI & Automation',
      summary: 'A telecommunications company deployed a custom GPT-powered chatbot that resolved 71% of customer enquiries without human intervention.',
    },
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: 'Custom App Development', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'Healthcare Software', href: '/services/custom-app-development' },
    { title: 'API Development & Integration', href: '/services/api-development' },
    { title: 'Cloud Infrastructure', href: '/services/cloud-infrastructure' },
  ],
};
